<DOC><DOCNO> AP890727-0101 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1352EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-Inspections-Soviet     07-27 0157</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Inspections-Soviet,140</SECOND><HEAD>US Observers Watch as Soviets Destroy Missiles</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   American inspectors watched the Soviet Uniondestroy the last of its 718 SS-12 shorter-range nuclear missiles inSaryozek, Kazakhstan, the Pentagon said Thursday.   The destruction took place under the terms of theIntermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty, which went into effect inJune 1988. The treaty requires that each side conduct on-siteinspections of each other's eliminations.   The Soviet Union has notified the United States that it willbegin elimination of its other shorter-range missile, the SS-23Spider on Aug. 17.   The United States destroyed the last of its shorter-rangemissiles, the Pershing 1A, on July 6 at Longhorn Army AmmunitionPlant in Texas.   Under the treaty, the shorter-range missiles, which travelbetween 500 kilometers and 1,000 kilometers, must be eliminated byNov. 30, 1989.   The intermediate range weapons, with ranges of between 1,000kilometers and 5,000 kilometers, must be destroyed by May 31, 1991.</TEXT></DOC>